member.summary:
Reasoned exceptions require an enum to identify the reason for the exception. The enum Description attribute carries the message for the exception. This gives you a concise list of all of the reasons you expect an exception to be thrown and collates all of the messages into one place. The reason descriptions can contain parameter placeholders that will be passed to string.Format. If the Description attribute is repeated as the enum value XML summary documentation then you will also get intellisense on the message associated with the reason.
Define the reason as follows; public enum YourExceptionReason { <summary> An unknown exception occurred inside the method: {0} </summary> [Description("An unknown exception occurred inside the method: {0}")] UnknownException, <summary> The widget diameter of {0} was out of range. At this point it should be between {1} & {2}. </summary> [Description("The widget diameter of {0} was out of range. At this point it should be between {1} & {2}.")] WidgetDiameterOutOfRange }
public class YourException : ReasonedException<YourExceptionReason> ....
The exception would then be thrown as; throw new YourException(YourExceptionReason.WidgetDiameterOutOfRange, widget.Diameter, MinWidgetDiameter, MaxWidgetDiameter);
